5|$|Early Mormons {{understood}} the Book <b>of</b> <b>Mormon</b> to be a religious {{history of the}} indigenous peoples of the Americas. Smith's followers {{view it as a}} companion to the Bible and an additional witness of Christ, akin to a large apocryphal work. Modern historian Fawn Brodie has called the Book <b>of</b> <b>Mormon</b> a response to pressing cultural and environmental issues of Smith's times, saying that Smith composed the Book <b>of</b> <b>Mormon</b> drawing from scraps of information available to him. Dan Vogel, another historian, says that the work is autobiographical in nature.|$|E
